1) both the solar phase and earth longitude have a linear relationship with time, which is expected. From the 2d plot of particle count and solar phase, the probability distribution is the same regardless of the phase, which we can conclude that the solar phase is independent of particle count. However, there's a clear shift of probability distribution of particle count due to earth longitude. Given the detection of cosmic ray has, the background is expected to have Poisson pdf() with mean shift over earth longitude.

2) There exist signal contamination as the reading value of the background and stars varys image by image. Image background is not time dependent as the data are in one image and it is spatially consistent.

To find a supernova, I first need to get rid of the stars and the background noise. To do this, I can subtract the images. However since I'm looking for a suprnova, I can first select an image and then subtract its background with the average background of the other nine image. If there exists a signal of the supernova, then anything that is above 5-sigma of the substracted pdf is considered as the supernova. Notice the width of the pdf strinks as we avrage more images, so we have to be aware of that.

    sigma = np.std(imgSub)

    x = np.linspace(mean -5*sigma,mean + 5*sigma,1000)
    d = stats.norm(mean, sigma).pdf(x)

3) The property of a transient should be a rapid rise of signal, but apparently, there's none from all ten images. I couldn't find a transient as shown from the above figures that there exists not a single clear signal rise above th 5-sigma threshold of the pdf of subtracted noise. I averaged all the images' background except for the selected image and did this for all ten images. This is probabily the bug of coding.

4.Though we use the same data, the question which we address are different, meaning the signal pdf that we are looking are different. For finding the transient, I need to look for the signal that appears in one image and should have a clear rise of pixel value, so the pdf I'm looking for should be noticabley different from one of the ten images. For looking at the dimmiest stars, since the property of stars is that they are constant, my partner can just take the average of the ten images, get the pdf and find the 5-sigma threshold for discovery.
